<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="85db23c5460edbab2bf0e407e3b94fba" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Sauron Culture for Dummies. Or Why Hate Does NOT Belong in Your Swarm.<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.89)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=13760'>John "Nobody Home" Doe</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=13760&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 15, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> (Note: This is my first article on Decktech, so go easy on me. Also it’s really geared toward novice Sauron players, so keep that in mind as well.)<br />
<br />
    It seems that Sauron culture has gotten pretty popular recently. Sauron swarming in particular has seen a huge increase in popularity (if you don’t believe me, check out the Deck Designs message board on Decipher’s LOTR page). I’m not particularly surprised. After all, Sauron swarms have always been good! They just needed a few changes in the meta-game to show it.<br />
    That said, I’ve noticed a common problem emerging in this new rash of Sauron deck postings, specifically those sporting the title of “Sauron Swarm.” They often suffer from an unfortunately common dysfunction known as “Deck Schizophrenia.” Deck Schizophrenia is an illness common in Sauron players (and occasionally Isengard fans) who find themselves faced with so many excellent cards that they suffer a brief, but complete mental meltdown resulting in a deck with no distinguishable identity.<br />
    In your typical schizophrenic Sauron deck, it seems the owner just can’t decide whether he/she wants to swarm the enemy  with Taskmasters, Spies, Teeth, and trackers; wound them to death with Hate, UTWE, and Orc Bowmen; or just go for the old fashioned one on one beatdown with a nasty looking Morgul Hunter (man that guy has a cool picture!). <br />
The problem is, most of these cards are actually quite good! Teeth of Mordor has been dubbed “Goblin Swarms for Mordor”, and Hate has often been voted the single best card in LOTR (I don’t care if you agree or not, it’s undeniably a great card).<br />
    This is the problem facing those who want to make a deck out of the Sauron culture: there’s just so much good stuff that we don’t know where to begin. Sauron is probably the most diverse culture out there (although Isengard gives it a good run for its money). So a bit of Deck Schizophrenia is probably not too surprising.<br />
    My hope with this article is to help demystify the Sauron culture a bit. Of course, swarming has always been my forte, but hopefully there’s something in here for everyone. Again, this article is geared towards those who are relatively new to the Sauron culture, I doubt the expert Sauron players will find anything new here (Though I’d welcome their comments!).<br />
<br />
There’s 5 major winning strategies you can take with Sauron (not including strategies that mix Sauron with other cultures). I’m going to list each of them including the general winning strategy behind them and good cards to include with the strategy.<br />
<br />
1)Sauron Wounding: <br />
4 copies each of Hate, Orc Bowmen and Under the Watching Eye (UTWE) along with a lot of trackers and exert to wound orcs. Very nasty, and probably one of the most popular Sauron strategies out there. You Bring Great Evil sees some play here. Enquea (the Fellowship version) is pretty much a no-brainer. The main damage comes from UTWE and Bowmen. The exert-to-wound orcs are just along for the ride and to get an occasional wound in. It’s vital to have at least 12 trackers in the deck to allow you to play UTWE. Orc Scouting Band fills 2 roles in this deck and 4 copies should always be included (Orc Cutthroat is a good match too). By the way, multiple copies of I’d Make You Squeak can really go nuts with this strategy (people often use their hobbits as pincushions) presenting a viable counter to various choke strategies.<br />
<br />
2)Sauron Corruption: <br />
This strategy has gotten a lot of new attention since Gollum, Stinker showed up on the scene (though unfortunately, less attention than Easterling and Nazgul corruption). The idea revolves around 4 copies of Desperate Defense of the Ring (DDotR) and a couple copies of Thin and Stretched to force the FP player to make some hard decisions. Gleaming in the Snow and Enduring Evil often find their way into these decks along with the occasional Verily I Come. Minions tend to be big like Morgul Hunter or Orc Pillager. Aside from Gollum, there have been many attempts to combine this deck concept with Nazgul or Easterling burdening.<br />
<br />
3)Sauron Smack-down: <br />
Bears some similarity to Sauron Corruption. Basically, you throw out a really powerful minion with a lot of vitality and nice strength boosting ability like Morgul Hunter, Morgul Warden, Orc Pillager, Orc Trooper and so forth. Vile Blades figure in big (when slapped on an Orc Swordsman it can almost be ridiculous), and so do big fighting boosts like Enheartened Foe, and Orc Banner. Enduring Evil makes an appearance, which often prompts inclusion of burdening cards like DDotR and Thin and Stretched. Since the big guys aren’t damage +1, or naturally fierce, the goal is to overwhelm companions, or at least intimidate the opponent into single moving the whole game while the fellowship runs for the win.<br />
<br />
4)Sauron Discard: <br />
This one has lost a lot of steam since the site path switched to The Two Towers. But I think the main reason no one plays this much is that it doesn’t take long for those who regularly play this deck to basically lose all their friends. Trust me, losing your entire deck before you get halfway through the game is probably the epitome of a “negative play experience” (NPE). Only use this on people you don’t plan on meeting ever again. The main concept is to “deck” your opponent (meaning there’s no draw deck left) by site 6 and using move limit modifying cards to run from site 6 to 9 virtually unopposed. This used to be done using the Elf card Gift of Boats until we lost all our river sites in Two Towers. It might still be done with the new site path utilizing cards like Safe Paths or News from the Mark. To really work this strategy also requires the Free Peoples half to be discarding the opponent’s cards too. Dwarves and Elves (with Shoulder to Shoulder) were the obvious choices until Gift of Boats went obsolete.<br />
Anyway, here’s the cards that see play here. Minions include: Band of the Eye, Orc Inquisitor, Tower Lieutenant, Orc Warrior and basically any minion with a lot of vitality. Other cards to include are DDotR, Desperate Measures, His Cruelty and Malice and 4x Tower of Baradur. Other useful cards are The Dark Lord Advances, Hand of Sauron, Southern Spies, and Massing in the East. Be sure to include Tower Assassin since Old Noakes can really ruin your day.<br />
On a final note, Frodo, Courteous Halfling ruins the whole thing, and if you play this strategy enough, he’ll show up rather quickly.<br />
<br />
5)And finally, Sauron Swarm: <br />
This strategy seems counterintuitive at first glance. How are you supposed to swarm with minions that roam until site 6? Fear not, it’s quite possible. <br />
The first concern is to make your minions as cheap as possible. This is accomplished through the liberal use of trackers and cheap minions. You want your minions to be a cost of two, TOPS. If you want to include a 3 or 4 cost minion, that minion’s ability better be hands-down outstanding (like Grishnak). Otherwise, forget it. Don’t worry about not having large minions. If you get enough of them out, no one’s going to notice. Besides, you can include 4x Orc Butcher. 2 cost for a minion that can easily go strength 12 in this sort of deck is just plain nasty!<br />
Second, you need to set up a wicked card drawing machine. In the old days, this used to be done with Spies of Mordor (late game, with 4 of this card out and a tracker, you could draw 8 cards in the regroup phase!) or even Seeking Its Master (though Spies is certainly the better card). The problem with Spies was that Sleep Caradhras or Secret Sentinels at site 6 or 7 could just ruin everything. Now there are more options available. Just about every Sauron orc in BOHD has a card drawing ability. These drawing abilities aren’t really that impressive all by themselves, but combined with 2 or 3 Morannon and 2 or 3 Spies, they’ll get the job done nicely.<br />
The final concern is twilight generation. It is here, the swarm finds its weakness. Sauron swarms are certainly no where near the caliber of Moria swarms in twilight generation. The swarm took a real hit with the X-listing of Forces of Mordor which lost them the only good twilight generation they had. I’d Make You Squeak is a possible replacement, but getting the wounds on the hobbits becomes problematic (really, it only works reliably in a wounding deck). This may be something Sauron players just have to live with (although some advocate including Moria’s Goblin Runners . . . the heretics!). A more interesting option is to combine some of the new site control orcs (Orc Infantry, Fighter, and Captain) with Orc Banner. Looks promising, but we’ll have to see how it pans out.<br />
Other good cards are Teeth of Mordor (mandatory in my opinion) and Seeking It Always (but only if Stealth events are big in your meta).  The Eye of Barad Dur is actually not too shabby in this deck since you’re guaranteed at least one ring-bound companion and a -1 strength on Frodo can make all the difference when going for the overwhelm (of course it’s the bomb against Ring-Bound Rangers (RBRs)).<br />
Try and shoot for a massive swarm somewhere after site 6 (when everyone stops roaming). It might be possible to swarm at site five, but usually you’ll just be getting set up all the way to 6. By this point the unwary will be getting pretty confident and will make that fatal double move, and that’s when you release the hounds!<br />
That’s the swarm. Sorry for being extra long winded, but this is my baby. Besides, the swarm seems to be the new fad on the web right now so I thought it deserved extra air time.<br />
<br />
KEY POINT!!! If you don’t remember anything else about this article, remember this: Except for the smack-down and corruption strategies (which share a lot of cards), NONE OF THESE STRATEGIES MIX WELL TOGETHER! Each strategy’s objective requires total commitment of cards. If you go only halfway, your cards won’t be able to do the job. <br />
If you try to throw in Sauron Wounding with the Swarm (which seems to be the most common mistake among Sauron newbies), neither will work. You’ll cause some wounds, but not enough to win, and you won’t have everything you need to swarm having wasted the card slots on wounding stuff.<br />
<br />
That said, there are a few cards that are useful in just about any strategy:<br />
<br />
1-Grishnak: This guy is amazing! Wonderful cost for the stats you’re getting. His card draw/burdening ability is solid, but his ability to reduce your orcs’ site number by 3 is just fantastic! Site number reduction is far preferable to roaming cost reduction (due to Ring-bound Rangers). This is probably the only cost 4 guy I’d allow in a swarm.<br />
<br />
2-Tower Assassin: Again, huge stats for the cost, and he can annihilate most allies (although Elrond can take it). Works well in any strategy except the Swarm. I’m sure I’m going to take some flak for this, but Memory of Many Things is probably better in the cost-conscious swarm (and being able to ace 2 Elf allies is huge). Incidentally, Memory works well in most strategies too, but Tower Assassin is probably better non-swarming decks (he’s mandatory in the Smack-Down deck).<br />
<br />
3-Shadow’s Reach: Some conditions really hurt, so being able to rid yourself of them can be crucial. This card fits the bill better than anything else I know.  Orc Guard stinks (like a Sauron player would ever want to discard his conditions). Orc Patrol from BOHD is good, but his cost of 4 makes me hesitant to use him in a swarm when I’ve already thrown in 2 or 3 Grishnak. Gate Sentry is even worse in a swarm since he doesn’t reduce the site number. These 2 minions are probably worth considering in other decks though.<br />
<br />
4-Dead Marshes: I don’t know of a single Sauron strategy that doesn’t have lots of nasty conditions out at a given moment. And I can’t think of a better way to annihilate a Sauron deck than packing some simple condition removal. Things have gotten better since Grima, Chief Counselor. Gandalf, with his weapons of mass condition removal, is no longer a throw-in companion, and people even have to think hard about including Elf allies for Secret Sentinels. However, Gondor (Athelas) and Rohan (Fortress Never Fallen) are very popular, and Elves still show up in a lot of places. <br />
No, I’d still say it’s just plain foolhardy to go into battle without Dead Marshes, the ONLY condition protection Sauron has as of yet. Pack about 2 if conditions are really important, pack 1 regardless.<br />
<br />
5-Eye of Barad Dur: I wasn’t sure about this one, but I knew I’d take flak if I didn’t list it. In open format where people still Sting each other’s hands, it’s mandatory. Closed format . . . well, it still amounts to a solid strength boost. That’s great for Smack-down decks and possibly swarm decks. But anything else? I personally think there’s better cards out there for other strategies. Of course it’s a great meta card if RBRs or Frodo-Sam-Smeagol choke decks give you headaches.<br />
<br />
6-No. I’m not going to include the Gate Troll. It’s just too early to say anything of the sort about him.<br />
<br />
7-Orc Insurgent would be on here if everyone wasn’t so scared of Grima.<br />
<br />
Now let’s list a few cards that LOOK like they’d be useful in multiple strategies, but aren’t:<br />
<br />
1-Vile Blade (and the same goes for Orc Scimitar): OK, Vile Blade is a great card and since Gondor, Rohan and Elves are still the most popular cultures out there (and probably in that order), this card is still solid. <br />
But let’s look at the nature of the card. Its purpose is to help a SINGLE minion win a skirmish. With Uruk-hai that is almost always a good thing. But there are times with Sauron when winning a one-on-one is pretty much pointless. In the swarm we don’t care if your single minion wins a skirmish because he isn’t going to cause more than one wound (remember Sauron orcs are never dmg +1, and aren’t naturally fierce). One wound. Whoopee. Why are you wasting time winning fights when you should be shooting for an overwhelm with 5 to 7 minions on one companion. If your single orcs are able to overwhelm with a Vile Blade, it probably means they’re too big to be in your swarm in the 1st place, and you should be attempting a Sauron Smack-down instead. Smack-down is the ONE strategy that Vile Blade actually belongs in since Discard, Wounding, and even Corruption don’t care if you win your skirmishes or not.<br />
<br />
2-Orc Scouting Band: Sure he’s a tracker, but he doesn’t belong in your swarm. He costs three and he doesn’t add anything to your swarm strategy that a cheaper cost 2 or 1 tracker couldn’t do. The same MAY also be true for Orc Cutthroat. The only problem is that excellent site number -3 ability . . . Can you tell I’m having a hard time figuring out Orc Cutthroat and Patrol?<br />
<br />
3-Any of the wounding cards. Hate, Bowmen, UTWE. They don’t belong in any deck but Wounding. I know this is redundant, but I have to emphasize this because of all the Hates I see listed in supposed “Swarm” decks (also, I know I’m going to get blasted about this by someone, so I might as well defend myself now). <br />
Unless you go all out with the wounding cards, they don’t work. They won’t kill enough companions and they might not kill any. The truth is, Hate just plain stinks in any deck but wounding. Sauron orcs are not Uruk-hai. They don’t cause very many wounds at all, even when they are winning their skirmishes. They certainly won’t cause enough wounds for the 2 copies of Hate you threw in to make one bit of difference. I’ve got a new mantra for beginning players. Take a deep breath. Now, repeat after me. “Wounds do not equal winning.” Repeat 9 times.<br />
<br />
That’s my lengthy explanation of the basics of the Sauron culture. With Sauron, there are many paths to victory. But you’ve got to pick just ONE of those paths. Hopping back and forth will only get you lost. <br />
There are cards I’ve left out that don’t belong in any deck period (like Journey Into Danger). But I’m sure you don’t need me to tell you about them. I was going to post my swarm deck, but the article is already too long. I’ll post it if I get any requests.<br />
<br />
Good luck!<br />
